Here, you'll see lots of connectors or ports.

3
00:00:18,050 --> 00:00:21,725
We can plug in different objects like a mouse,

4
00:00:21,725 --> 00:00:24,730
keyboard, and a monitor.

5
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:27,475
These are known as peripherals.

6
00:00:27,475 --> 00:00:30,190
A peripheral is basically anything that you connect

7
00:00:30,190 --> 00:00:33,245
to your computer externally that adds functionality.

8
00:00:33,245 --> 00:00:35,650
You probably used USB devices before.

9
00:00:35,650 --> 00:00:37,540
USB, also known as

10
00:00:37,540 --> 00:00:42,790
Universal Serial Bus devices are the most popular connections for our gadgets.

11
00:00:42,790 --> 00:00:46,765
USB has gone through lots of changes since inception.

12
00:00:46,765 --> 00:00:49,430
You most commonly encounter USB 2.0,

13
00:00:49,430 --> 00:00:52,690
USB 3.0, and 3.1 in today's system.

14
00:00:52,690 --> 00:00:55,605
Here's a quick rundown of the different versions.

15
00:00:55,605 --> 00:01:00,610
USB 2.0 transfers speeds of 480 megabytes per second,

16
00:01:00,610 --> 00:01:05,225
USB 3.0 transfers speeds of five gigabytes per second,

17
00:01:05,225 --> 00:01:10,155
USB 3.1 transfers speeds of 10 gigabytes per second.

18
00:01:10,155 --> 00:01:13,890
In the chart, let's pay attention to the details.

19
00:01:13,890 --> 00:01:18,390
Using capital M lowercase b forward slash s instead

20
00:01:18,390 --> 00:01:23,250
of using capital M capital B to reference transfer speed.

21
00:01:23,250 --> 00:01:25,350
These are actually different units.

22
00:01:25,350 --> 00:01:30,226
MB is megabyte or unit of data storage,

23
00:01:30,226 --> 00:01:36,270
while capital M lower case b forward slash s is a megabit per second,

24
00:01:36,270 --> 00:01:39,140
which is a unit of data transfer rate.

25
00:01:39,140 --> 00:01:43,305
People often mistake speeds of 40 megabit per second

26
00:01:43,305 --> 00:01:47,825
to mean that you can transfer 40 megabytes of data per second.

27
00:01:47,825 --> 00:01:51,575
Remember, that one byte is 8 bits,

28
00:01:51,575 --> 00:01:54,300
so to transfer a one megabyte file in a

29
00:01:54,300 --> 00:01:59,265
second you need an 8 megabits per second connection speed.

30
00:01:59,265 --> 00:02:03,730
So, to transfer 40 megabytes of data in a second,

31
00:02:03,730 --> 00:02:08,645
you need a transfer speed of 240 megabits per second.

32
00:02:08,645 --> 00:02:12,780
You'll also need comparable USB ports to go with your devices.

33
00:02:12,780 --> 00:02:17,740
If you connect a USB 2.0 device into a USB 3.0 port,

34
00:02:17,740 --> 00:02:20,185
you won't get 3.0 transfer speeds.

35
00:02:20,185 --> 00:02:23,774
But you can still use the port since it's backward compatible,

36
00:02:23,774 --> 00:02:27,115
meaning older hardware work with newer hardware.

37
00:02:27,115 --> 00:02:29,960
The ports are easy to differentiate. Let me show you.

38
00:02:29,960 --> 00:02:38,055
In general, USB 2.0 are black and USB 3.0 are blue and 3.1 ports are teal.

39
00:02:38,055 --> 00:02:42,075
This may change depending on manufacturers.

40
00:02:42,075 --> 00:02:44,405
There are lots of types of USB connectors,

41
